{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476318"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:44:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:44:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13727"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13727"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.32,0.44,0.02,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6346"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102182"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6346"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13727"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84646"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2290"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9690"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11798"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18048"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18099"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18116"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35564"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42916"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44167"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102182"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-month-old girl presents to her General Practice clinic with her parents for a routine check. She was born at 39 weeks gestation with a birth weight of 3.2 kg (50th percentile). She is exclusively breastfed and her parents report she feeds every 3-4 hours for 20-30 minutes per feed. She has 6-8 wet nappies per day. Her parents have no other concerns. She has no significant medical history and her newborn screening tests were normal. On examination, she appears well with normal vital signs. Her weight is now 3.6 kg (3rd percentile). Head circumference and length are tracking along the 50th percentile.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important investigation to perform next?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serum amino acids","Sweat chloride test","Thyroid function tests","Serum lead level","Echocardiogram"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant has poor weight gain, with weight falling from the 50th to 3rd percentile. The first step is to take a detailed feeding history and perform a thorough physical examination. Red flags such as dysmorphic features or organomegaly should prompt specialist referral. Initial investigations should include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplete blood count\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EElectrolytes, urea and creatinine\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELiver function tests\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis, microscopy and culture\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECoeliac serology (if on solids or feeds containing gluten)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFerritin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlucose\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStool microscopy to assess for inadequate intake, malabsorption, or infection. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf these are unremarkable, less common causes such as endocrine disorders should be considered. Specific investigations for underlying metabolic, immune or genetic cause should be performed in consultation with specialist services.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid function tests\u003C/strong\u003E are an important second-line investigation in an infant with poor weight gain. While newborn screening includes thyroid function testing and can detect congenital hypothyroidism, acquired hypothyroidism can develop later in infancy. Therefore, thyroid function should be reassessed in cases of poor weight gain. Hypothyroidism can present with faltering growth, lethargy, feeding difficulties, and constipation. Prompt diagnosis and treatment with thyroxine supplementation is critical to prevent intellectual disability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECystic fibrosis can cause failure to thrive due to pancreatic insufficiency leading to malabsorption and increased metabolic demand from recurrent infections. However, additional features such as recurrent respiratory infections or fatty stools are usually present. \u003Cstrong\u003ESweat chloride testing\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there is clinical suspicion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInborn errors of metabolism are rare causes of failure to thrive. They are usually accompanied by other signs and symptoms such as seizures, vomiting, or altered mental status. \u003Cstrong\u003ESerum amino acids\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered if there are other suggestive features or if initial work-up is non-diagnostic, but is not the most important next investigation in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum lead levels\u003C/strong\u003E should be checked in at-risk infants with pica, developmental delay, or anaemia. However, this infant has no risk factors and her growth trajectory is more suggestive of an organic cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECongenital heart disease can cause failure to thrive due to increased metabolic demand and congestive cardiac failure. Additional signs such as a heart murmur, tachypnoea, or hepatomegaly are usually present. An \u003Cstrong\u003Eechocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there is clinical suspicion, but is not the most appropriate next investigation based on the information provided.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Failure to thrive requires a comprehensive work-up to identify the underlying cause, which may include inadequate caloric intake, malabsorption, increased metabolic demand, or psychosocial factors.","Key initial investigations for failure to thrive include a thorough dietary history, complete blood count, electrolytes, liver function tests, urinalysis, coeliac serology, and stool microscopy.","While newborn screening includes thyroid function, acquired hypothyroidism can develop later and should be considered in infants with poor weight gain."],"references":["Royal Children\u2019s Hospital Melbourne. Slow weight gain [Internet]. Melbourne: RCH; [cited 2025 May 10]. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Slow_weight_gain/","Duryea TK. Poor weight gain in children younger than two years in resource-abundant settings: Etiology and evaluation. In: UpToDate [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/poor-weight-gain-in-children-younger-than-two-years-in-resource-abundant-settings-etiology-and-evaluation","Pritchard N. A practical approach to the assessment of faltering growth in the infant and toddler. Paediatrics and Child Health. 2015;25(9):433-6. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S1751722215000931"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84646"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13727"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84646"},